This paper is about analyzing neural models of language, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses deep learning, which is a popular approach in machine learning, and thus cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. The methods presented in the paper involve quantifying the correspondence between neural activation patterns and symbolic structures, which involves both computational and algorithmic aspects, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions using Tree Kernels, which are commonly used in natural language processing and machine learning, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses applying the methods to English sentences, which may involve computer vision techniques for processing text, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a less likely but still possible sub-category.
